t: Ecclesiastes 10
Dead*p flies cause the ointment of the apothecary to send forth a stinking savour: so doth a little folly him that is in reputation for wisdom and honour.
A*p wise man's heart is at his right hand; but a fool's heart at his left.
Yea*p also, when he that is a fool walketh by the way, his wisdom faileth him, and he saith to every one that he is a fool.
If*p the spirit of the ruler rise up against thee, leave not thy place; for yielding pacifieth great offences.
There*p is an evil which I have seen under the sun, as an error which proceedeth from the ruler:
Folly*p is set in great dignity, and the rich sit in low place.
I*p have seen servants upon horses, and princes walking as servants upon the earth.
He*p that diggeth a pit shall fall into it; and whoso breaketh an hedge, a serpent shall bite him.
Whoso*p removeth stones shall be hurt therewith; and he that cleaveth wood shall be endangered thereby.
If*p the iron be blunt, and he do not whet the edge, then must he put to more strength: but wisdom is profitable to direct.
Surely*p the serpent will bite without enchantment; and a babbler is no better.
The*p words of a wise man's mouth are gracious; but the lips of a fool will swallow up himself.
The*p beginning of the words of his mouth is foolishness: and the end of his talk is mischievous madness.
A*p fool also is full of words: a man cannot tell what shall be; and what shall be after him, who can tell him?
The*p labour of the foolish wearieth every one of them, because he knoweth not how to go to the city.
Woe*p to thee, O land, when thy king is a child, and thy princes eat in the morning!
Blessed*p art thou, O land, when thy king is the son of nobles, and thy princes eat in due season, for strength, and not for drunkenness!
By*p much slothfulness the building decayeth; and through idleness of the hands the house droppeth through.
A*p feast is made for laughter, and wine maketh merry: but money answereth all things.
Curse*p not the king, no not in thy thought; and curse not the rich in thy bedchamber: for a bird of the air shall carry the voice, and that which hath wings shall tell the matter.
